# Openapi
Openapi docs should be contianed within the openapi-docs folder. The openapi-docs folder should have 4 subfolders: components, examples, integrations, and paths. All files with openapi-docs (except for .spectral) need to follow the OpenAPI Specification v3.0.1 as outlined in: https://spec.openapis.org/oas/v3.0.1.html. There should be a top-level index.yaml file that has openapi, info, servers, and paths. No other fields like components, security, or tags should be in the index.yaml file.

```
openapi: 3.0.1
info:
  title: WebScraper API
  description: REST API for the webscraper database.
  version: 1.0.0

servers:
  - url: https://api.example.com
    description: API Gateway base URL (override at deployment)

paths:
  /routes:
    $ref: './paths/getRoutes.yaml'
  /docs/{file}:
    $ref: './paths/getApiDocs.yaml'
```

## Paths
Paths should be separated into their own files within the openapi-docs/paths folder and referenced by index.yaml. Each path must have a comment at the top of the file with the uri of the route. Each path must contain a summary, description, operationId and responses. The name of the file must match the operationId of the path in the file and the filename/operationId should be in lower camel case. If the path should have a requestBody or response with a complicated schema (like a json object, more than just a simple string), it should reference the schema from the components folder. If a schema in the requestBody or responses references a component, it must also reference an example json. Each path that has parameters (path, query, header) or a requestBody must include a `400` response for failed request validation (e.g. missing required parameter, invalid body).

`opeanapi-docs/paths/getRoutes.yaml`
```
# /routes
get:
  summary: List all routes
  description: Returns all routes in the database.
  operationId: getRoutes
  tags:
    - routes
  x-amazon-apigateway-integration:
    $ref: '../integrations/getRoutesLambda.yaml#/GetRoutesLambdaIntegration'
  responses:
    '200':
      description: Successful response
      content:
        application/json:
          schema:
            $ref: '../components/routesResponse.yaml#/RoutesResponse'
          examples:
            getRoutesResponse:
              $ref: '../examples/getRoutesResponse.yaml'
    '500':
      description: Internal server error
```

The `$ref` is placed directly under the example name; the ref'd file contains the full [Example Object](https://spec.openapis.org/oas/v3.0.1.html#example-object-example) (summary and value).

## Components
Components should be separated into their own files in the openapi-docs/components folder. Each component file should have a primary component that is referenced in paths or integrations, but it may also have secondary components that are referenced by the primary components. The primary component should match the operationId of whichever path is referencing it, along with "Response" or "RequestBody" depending on what type of component it is. Component names should be in upper camel case, and the file should be the name of the primary component in lower camel case. Each property of an object needs a description, as well as the object itself. If a property is required, it should be be in the "required" list at the top of the object and if a property is nullable, it should have nullable: true. 

`openapi-docs/components/getRoutesResponse.yaml`
```
GetRoutesResponse:
  type: array
  items:
    $ref: "#/Route"

Route:
  type: object
  description: A single route with a set of coordinates for its marker
  required:
    - id
    - name
    - type
    - coordinates
  properties:
    id:
      type: string
      format: uuid
      description: Unique identifier for the route
    name:
      type: string
      description: Display name of the route
    type:
      type: string
      description: Route type
      enum:
        - Unknown
        - POI
        - Cave
        - Canyon
    coordinates:
      $ref: "#/Coordinates"

Coordinates:
  type: object
  description: The coordinates of the marker for a route
  required:
    - lat
    - lon
  properties:
    lat:
      type: number
      format: float
      description: Latitude of the coordinate
    lon:
      type: number
      format: float
      description: Longitute of the coordinate
```

## Examples
Examples live in the openapi-docs/examples folder as **.yaml** files. Each file is a full [Example Object](https://spec.openapis.org/oas/v3.0.1.html#example-object-example): include `summary` and `value`. The `value` is the example payload (JSON structure; you can write it in YAML). The path references it with the `$ref` directly under the example name (see Paths). File names should match the example key (e.g. getRoutesResponse.yaml). Use real-looking data where possible; for arrays include at least 2 items with variety.

`openapi-docs/examples/getRoutesResponse.yaml`
```yaml
summary: Sample GeoJSON Feature Collection of routes
value:
  type: FeatureCollection
  features:
    - type: Feature
      geometry: { type: Point, coordinates: [-111.456, 40.123] }
      properties: { id: "...", name: "Bear Creek Canyon", type: Canyon }
    - type: Feature
      ...
```

## Linting
Run `npm run lint:openapi` after changing openapi-docs and fix any **errors** so the linter exits cleanly.  

## Integrations
Integrations are for cloudformation to know how to attach each path to a invoke a lambda or get a file from S3. Integrations should be separated into their own files in the openapi-docs/integrations folder. Each integration needs an x-amazon-apigateway-integration object as defined in https://docs.aws.amazon.com/apigateway/latest/developerguide/api-gateway-swagger-extensions-integration.html. The integration object's name should be in upper camel case and match the path's operationId that it belongs to, followed by which service it uses (Lambda/S3) and then "Integration". The file's name should match the integration object's name in lower camel case, without the "Integration" at the end.

`openapi-docs/integrations/getRoutesLambda.yaml`
```
GetRoutesLambdaIntegration:
  type: aws_proxy
  httpMethod: POST
  uri: arn:aws:apigateway:$env-REGION:lambda:path/2015-03-31/functions/$env-GET_ROUTES_LAMBDA_ARN/invocations
  credentials: $env-APIGATEWAY_INVOKE_LAMBDA_ROLE_ARN
  passthroughBehavior: when_no_match
```